{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/diabetes-type-1/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-hypoglycaemia/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"2a892a37-ec75-5c0c-b79d-9b550ba6f44a","slug":"when-to-suspect-hypoglycaemia","fullItemName":"When to suspect hypoglycaemia","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 4f755d87-dd13-4c4c-8fb4-b2d12a7301e6 --><h2>When should I suspect hypoglycaemia in a person with type 1 diabetes?</h2><!-- end field 4f755d87-dd13-4c4c-8fb4-b2d12a7301e6 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b68d6451-fd92-4b2c-9736-d5b70a9fe477 --><!-- begin field 9940c7d2-1cc1-4e64-9ea5-d30106685ac9 --><ul><li><strong><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/diabetes-type-1/background-information/complications/\">Hypoglycaemia</a> presents with a wide variety of symptoms (autonomic and neuroglycopenic). </strong><ul><li><strong>Suspect mild hypoglycaemia in a person with type 1 diabetes who presents with the following:</strong><ul><li>Hunger.</li><li>Anxiety or irritability.</li><li>Sweating.</li><li>Tingling lips.</li><li>Irritability.</li><li>Palpitations.</li><li>Tremor.</li></ul></li><li><strong>As blood glucose levels fall lower, the person may experience:</strong><ul><li>Weakness and lethargy.</li><li>Impaired vision.</li><li>Incoordination.</li><li>Reduced orientation.</li><li>Confusion.</li><li>Irrational behaviour.</li><li>Emotional lability.</li><li>Deterioration of cognitive function (when blood glucose levels fall lower than 3.0 mmol/L).</li></ul></li><li><strong>Severe hypoglycaemia may result in:</strong><ul><li>Convulsions.</li><li>Inability to swallow.</li><li>Loss of consciousness.</li><li>Coma. </li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 9940c7d2-1cc1-4e64-9ea5-d30106685ac9 --><!-- end item b68d6451-fd92-4b2c-9736-d5b70a9fe477 -->","topic":{"id":"e0026a38-6f9d-5508-9a1c-f9cb4d041950","topicId":"83d7e1f3-89ef-4bb8-9e6c-8f19b4d34e87","topicName":"Dia